INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '4170d257-5eb8-4301-be42-7b42c02ea061',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Jest + React Testing Library — Testing Components Without Implementation Details$escape$,
  $escape$Jest alone doesn't render React components — it needs a DOM environment. With `@testing-library/react`, you render into a `jsdom` environment that Jest provides, then query and interact via user-facing selectors.

`render()` mounts the component. Query functions like `getByRole`, `getByText`, and `findByLabelText` target elements the way a user would — not by class names or test IDs. `getBy*` throws immediately if nothing matches; `findBy*` returns a Promise and retries until a timeout, essential for async state updates.

For interactions, use `userEvent` (v14+) over `fireEvent` — it simulates real browser behavior including focus, pointer events, and keyboard sequences. Always `await userEvent.setup()` before dispatching events.

Assertions land on `expect()` with jest-dom matchers: `toBeVisible()`, `toBeDisabled()`, `toHaveValue()`. These assertions inspect the rendered DOM, not component state — keeping tests resilient to refactors.

Wrap any render that triggers `setState` inside `act()`, or let RTL handle it automatically via `userEvent` and `findBy*` queries.$escape$,
  $escape$import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';
import { SubscribeButton } from './SubscribeButton';

test('disables button and shows loading after click', async () => {
  const user = userEvent.setup();
  render(<SubscribeButton onSubscribe={jest.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined)} />);

  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /subscribe/i }));

  expect(screen.getByRole('button')).toBeDisabled();
  expect(await screen.findByText(/subscribed!/i)).toBeVisible();
});$escape$,
